---

Multi-session long-horizon workflow. Use this command when a project spans more than one agent session.

## Session bootstrap

<session_bootstrap>
For any task spanning more than one session:
1. `pwd`                                   — confirm workspace
2. `cat claude-progress.txt`              — what was done last
3. `git log --oneline -20`                — recent commits
4. `jq '.[] | select(.passes==false)' feature_list.json`
5. `./init.sh` + smoke test               — is baseline working?
6. Pick ONE feature with passes==false
7. Implement it
8. Verify end-to-end (browser / curl / integration)
9. `git add -A && git commit -m "feat: <feature>"`
10. Update feature_list.json: passes=true (flip only after verification)
11. Append to claude-progress.txt: what you did, known issues, next step
Only then: end session.

Do not try to finish multiple features in one session.
Do not flip passes=true without end-to-end verification.
Do not edit or remove feature entries — only flip the passes field.
</session_bootstrap>

## Phase 1 — Initialise (first session only)

Run this phase once, before any coder session.

1. Create a dedicated branch from up-to-date `<%= mainBranch %>`:

```bash
git checkout <%= mainBranch %> && git pull origin <%= mainBranch %> && git checkout -b feature/<short-kebab-name>
```

2. Write `feature_list.json` — one entry per independent deliverable. Use JSON, not Markdown, so the agent cannot silently rewrite it.

```json
[
  { "id": "feat-1", "title": "<feature title>", "passes": false },
  { "id": "feat-2", "title": "<feature title>", "passes": false }
]
```

**Contract:** `passes: false` must stay `false` until full end-to-end verification succeeds. Only flip it to `true` after step 8 of the bootstrap protocol above.

3. Write `claude-progress.txt` with a single line: `Initialised. No sessions completed yet.`

4. Write `init.sh` — idempotent setup script (install deps, seed DB, start services):

```bash
<%- tooling.packageManagerPrefix %> install
```

5. Run `<%= commands.test %>` to confirm baseline is green before any coder session starts.

## Phase 2 — Coder sessions (repeat per session)

At the start of **every** session, execute the full `<session_bootstrap>` protocol above without skipping steps.

Then for the ONE feature you picked:

1. Use the `architect` sub-agent to draft a focused mini-plan (max 5 tasks) for this feature only.
2. Use the `implementer` sub-agent to execute each task.
3. After each task, run `code-reviewer` on modified files and apply all critical/warning findings.
4. <% if (commands.typeCheck) { %>Run `<%= commands.typeCheck %>` — must pass.<% } else { %>Run type checks (skip: no type-check command configured).<% } %>
5. Run `<%= commands.test %>` — must pass.
6. Verify end-to-end (browser / curl / integration test).
7. `git add -A && git commit -m "feat: <feature-id> <title>"` (conventional commit).
8. Flip `passes` to `true` in `feature_list.json` for this feature.
9. Append a progress entry to `claude-progress.txt`:

```
[YYYY-MM-DD] feat-N: <what was done>. Known issues: <none or describe>. Next: <next feature or "all done">.
```

## Phase 3 — Done

All features done when:

```bash
jq '[.[] | select(.passes==false)] | length' feature_list.json
# → 0
```

Run the final review loop:

1. `reviewer` sub-agent on all modified files.
2. `implementer` applies all critical/warning findings.
3. <% if (commands.typeCheck) { %>`<%= commands.typeCheck %>` — must pass.<% } else { %>Run type checks (skip: no type-check command configured).<% } %>
4. `<%= commands.test %>` — must pass.
<% if (commands.lint) { %>5. `<%= commands.lint %>` — must pass.
<% } %>
Then invoke `/external-review` as the final cross-model gate.

Print a final summary: features completed, files changed, any open issues.

The user will review and merge when satisfied.

